%description:
Regression test for RFC 5036 Section 2.4.2 extended discovery / targeted Hellos
(commit C10): ~Ldp.targetedPeers/~acceptTargetedHellos (both default off).

Ad hoc 3-LSR CHAIN: LSR1 -- LSR2 -- LSR3 (two links; LSR1 and LSR3 are NOT directly
connected -- no shared link, no local TED link between them). LSR1's targetedPeers
is configured with LSR3's LSR-ID; LSR3 has acceptTargetedHellos=true (the plan's
"symmetric targetedPeers on both, your choice" alternative -- this file uses the
asymmetric target/accept split since it exercises both new parameters). Unlike
ldp_loop_detection.test, this network relies entirely on ~Ted's own default
(installRoutes=true) shortest-path route computation, fed by ~LinkStateRouting's
flooding -- LSR1's targeted (unicast) Hello to LSR3 needs a REAL two-hop IPv4 route
through LSR2, which is exactly what Ted computes automatically for a genuinely
connected topology (no hand-written routing-loop trickery needed here).

Asserted:
  1. LSR1 actually attempts the targeted Hello (EV line quoting the destination).
  2. A session between the non-adjacent pair (LSR1<->LSR3) reaches OPERATIONAL --
     the same "LDP session with X is now OPERATIONAL" EV line
     (Ldp::processKEEPALIVE) any regular session uses; there is nothing
     targeted-specific about session establishment once the Hello adjacency exists.
  3. The regular hello adjacencies LSR1<->LSR2 and LSR2<->LSR3 ALSO establish their
     own sessions independently -- asserted via the sessionUp signal's scalar count
     (@statistic in Ldp.ned): 3 sessions total, each side of each session emits
     sessionUp once = 6 total emits summed across LSR1/LSR2/LSR3's
     "sessionUp:count" scalars. This is the precise, unambiguous way to prove
     "three sessions, not just the targeted one" -- the EV log alone can't
     disambiguate which of two textually-identical "is now OPERATIONAL" lines
     (same peer LSR-ID can appear once from the regular-adjacency side and once
     from the targeted side) came from which relationship.

Falsification: this test FAILS against the parent commit -- targetedPeers/
acceptTargetedHellos do not exist there (unknown parameter), and even given a
stashed-in .ned addition alone (no code), LSR1's targeted Hello would never be
sent (no such code path) and Ted::linkIndex() would ASSERT (debug build) the
moment LSR3 (not locally adjacent to LSR1) tried to process a Hello from it
through the old, unconditional TED-link code path -- so this scenario cannot
even survive to a passing state without this commit's Ted::isLocalPeer() guard.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: TargetedChain.ned

import inet.node.mpls.LdpMplsRouter;

//
// Ad hoc 3-LSR chain: LSR1 -- LSR2 -- LSR3. LSR1 and LSR3 share no link.
//
network TargetedChain
{
    parameters:
        **.ipv4.configurator.networkConfiguratorModule = "";
    submodules:
        LSR1: LdpMplsRouter {
            @display("p=200,150");
            gates: pppg[1];
        }
        LSR2: LdpMplsRouter {
            @display("p=400,150");
            gates: pppg[2];
        }
        LSR3: LdpMplsRouter {
            @display("p=600,150");
            gates: pppg[1];
        }
    connections:
        LSR1.pppg[0] <--> { delay = 1ms; datarate = 1Mbps; } <--> LSR2.pppg[0];
        LSR2.pppg[1] <--> { delay = 1ms; datarate = 1Mbps; } <--> LSR3.pppg[0];
}

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# Addressing: LSR1.ppp0=10.1.1.1 <-> LSR2.ppp0=10.1.1.2 (link A)
%#             LSR2.ppp1=10.1.2.1 <-> LSR3.ppp0=10.1.2.2 (link B)
%# routerId="auto" picks the HIGHEST interface address per LSR:
%#   LSR1 routerId = 10.1.1.1 (only interface)
%#   LSR2 routerId = max(10.1.1.2, 10.1.2.1) = 10.1.2.1
%#   LSR3 routerId = 10.1.2.2 (only interface)
%# No unicast routes are hand-written -- Ted (installRoutes left at its default
%# true) computes them, including the 2-hop LSR1<->LSR3 path, from LinkStateRouting's
%# flooded topology.
%file: LSR1.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.1.1.1	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 1
ifconfigend.

route:
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp0
routeend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: LSR2.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.1.1.2	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 1
name: ppp1	inet_addr: 10.1.2.1	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 1
ifconfigend.

route:
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp0
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp1
routeend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: LSR3.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.1.2.2	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 1
ifconfigend.

route:
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp0
routeend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%inifile: test.ini

[General]
ned-path = .;../../../../src
network = TargetedChain
sim-time-limit = 10s
total-stack = 64MiB
record-vector-results = false
cmdenv-express-mode = false
cmdenv-event-banners = false
**.ldp.cmdenv-log-level = info
**.cmdenv-log-level = off
output-scalar-file = "${resultdir}/${configname}-#${runnumber}.sca"

**.LSR1.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "LSR1.rt"
**.LSR2.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "LSR2.rt"
**.LSR3.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "LSR3.rt"

**.ppp[*].queue.typename = "DropTailQueue"
**.ppp[*].queue.packetCapacity = 10

**.holdTime = 3s
**.helloInterval = 1s

# RFC 5036 Section 2.4.2: LSR1 targets LSR3's LSR-ID directly; LSR3 accepts any
# requesting targeted peer (the asymmetric alternative the plan allows)
**.LSR1.ldp.targetedPeers = "10.1.2.2"
**.LSR3.ldp.acceptTargetedHellos = true

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# 1. LSR1 actually attempts the targeted Hello toward LSR3's LSR-ID
%contains: stdout
Sending targeted LDP Hello to 10.1.2.2
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# 2. the non-adjacent LSR1<->LSR3 session reaches OPERATIONAL (same EV line any
%# session uses -- Ldp::processKEEPALIVE -- nothing targeted-specific once the
%# Hello adjacency exists)
%contains: stdout
LDP session with 10.1.2.2 is now OPERATIONAL
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# 3. three sessions total (2 regular + 1 targeted), not just the targeted one:
%# each side of each session emits sessionUp once = 6 total emits summed across
%# all three LSRs' sessionUp:count scalars
%postrun-command: grep "sessionUp:count" results/General-#0.sca | awk '{s+=$NF} END{print s}' > sessionup_total.out
%contains: sessionup_total.out
6
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%postrun-command: grep "undisposed object:" test.out > test_undisposed.out || true
%not-contains: test_undisposed.out
undisposed object: (
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
